 Real Madrid CF website\n*[https://www.chelseafc.com/en/teams/first-team/mateo-kovacic?pageTab=biography Profile] at the Chelsea C.F. website\n*{{UEFA player}}\n*{{FIFA player}}\n\n{{Chelsea F.C. squad}}\n{{Croatian Football Hope of the Year award}}\n{{Navboxes\n| title = Croatia squads\n| bg = white\n| fg = #171796\n| bordercolor= red\n| list1 = \n{{Croatia squad 2014 FIFA World Cup}}\n{{Croatia squad UEFA Euro 2016}}\n{{Croatia squad 2018 FIFA World Cup}}\n}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Kovacic, Mateo}}\n[[Category:1994 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Austrian people of Croatian descent]]\n[[Category:Croats of Bosnia and Herzegovina]]\n[[Category:Austrian people of Bosnia and Herzegovina descent]]\n[[Category:Croatian people of Bosnia and Herzegovina descent]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Linz]]\n[[Category:Austrian footballers]]\n[[Category:Croatian footballers]]\n[[Category:Association football midfielders]]\n[[Category:GNK Dinamo Zagreb players]]\n[[Category:Inter Milan players]]\n[[Category:Real Madrid CF players]]\n[[Category:Chelsea F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Croatian First Football League players]]\n[[Category:Serie A players]]\n[[Category:La Liga players]]\n[[Category:Premier League players]]\n[[Category:UEFA Champions League winning players]]\n[[Category:UEFA Europa League winning players]]\n[[Category:Croatia under-21 international footballers]]\n[[Category:Croatia international footballers]]\n[[Category:2014 FIFA World Cup players]]\n[[Category:UEFA Euro 2016 players]]\n[[Category:2018 FIFA World Cup players]]\n[[Category:Croatian expatriate footballers]]\n[[Category:Croatian expatriate sportspeople in Italy]]\n[[Category:Croatian expatriate sportspeople in Spain]]\n[[Category:Croatian expatriate sportspeople in England]]\n[[Category:Expatriate footballers in Italy]]\n[[Category:Expatriate footballers in Spain]]\n[[Category:Expatriate footballers in England]]\n", "name_user": "Mk2023", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mateo_Kova%C4%8Di%C4%87"}
{"title_page": "Regulation Colours", "text_new": "[[File:Commonwealth Heads of Government Meeting MOD 45164080.jpg|thumb|The Queen's colour of the [[Coldstream Guards]].]]\nThe '''Regulation Colours''' are the standard colours used in the armed forces of the countries falling under the [[Commonwealth of Nations]].\n\n== [[British Armed Forces]] colours ==\n\n[[United Kingdom]] [[military]] units usually carry two '''Regulation Colours'''. These are the Regulation Queen's Colour and Regulation Regimental Colour. These are often referred to as the [[standard (flag)|standard]] or [[ensign]].\n\nColours are the identifying [[war flag|battle flag]]s carried by military [[regiment]]s to show where their respective [[troops]] should rally in battle. Originally these were 6'6\" x 6' in size, though have now been reduced to 3'9\" x 3', as regiments no longer carry their colours on the battlefield.\n\n=== British Army ===\n\nPrior to 1743, each infantry regiment of the [[British Army]] was responsible for the design and quantity of standards carried, often with each company having its own design. In that year King [[George II of Great Britain|George II]] issued a [[Warrant (law)|royal warrant]] to require each regiment to have, as their first colour, the King's colour. It was also to consist of the [[Union Jack]] throughout, as a symbol of royal allegiance. The second colour was to be the colour of the facings (uniform linings) of each Regiment, with the Union flag in the upper canton. When Regiments had red or white facings, this was to be replaced by the red cross of [[St George]] on a white background. Regiments with \"Royal\" designation or named after the members of the royal family, regardless of facings, used blue regimental colours (plus the optional Union Jack canton), Irish regiments green facings.\n\nA second royal warrant was issued in 1747, requiring the Regimental number to be displayed on the colours. As many regiments at that time were known by the name of the Regimental Colonel instead of a number, this requirement was often ignored. On 1 July 1751 a third royal warrant was issued stating ''\"No Colonel is to put his Arms, Crest, Device, or Livery on any part of the Appointments of the Regiment under his Command.\"'' Company colours were phased out altogether, with the battalion colours of the regiment using the designs issued being the only sanctioned ones used.\n\nOver time, these colours have evolved to include the battle honours s awarded to each Regiment, though these have also been limited.\n\n[[File:DWR Regimental Colours RLH.jpg|thumb|600px|Colours of the [[Duke of Wellington's Regiment]]]]\nOnly one British Regiment carries more than two colours on parade. This is the [[Yorkshire Regiment]], who carry four colours. The second pair consists of a stand of honorary battle flags, which are the original size of 6'6\" x 6'. These honorary colours, 'Queen's Honorary Colour' and 'Regimental Honorary Colour,' were originally awarded to the [[76th Regiment of Foot]], which later became the 2nd Battalion of the [[Duke of Wellington's Regiment|Duke of Wellington's (West Riding Regiment)]] in 1808, by the Honorable [[British East India Company|East India Company]] for their distinguished services during the [[Battle of Ally Ghur]] and again at [[Delhi]] between 1802 and 1804.<ref>[http://www.army.mod.uk/documents/general/YORKS_Honorary_Colours.pdf British Army website - Yorks Honorary Colours]</ref> In 1948 the 1st and 2nd Battalions merged and retained the Honorary Colours. In 2006 the Duke of Wellington's Regiment merged with the [[Prince of Wales's Own Regiment of Yorkshire]] and the [[Green Howards]] to form the 'Yorkshire Regiment (14th/15th, 19th and 33rd/76th Foot)'.<ref>[http://www.army.mod.uk/infantry/regiments/26215.aspx British Army website - Yorkshire Regiment History]</ref>\n\nLight infantry regiments (today [[The Rifles]]) plus the [[Brigade of Gurkhas]] do not use colours at all owing to their role (the latter, however, carries the Queen's Truncheon awarded in 1857 instead).\n\n==== [[Guards Division]] ====\nUnlike the rest of the Army, all five [[Foot Guards]] infantry regiments sport a different variant pattern.\n\nGiven the status of the guards regiments as units under royal patronage and for the defence of the British Royal Family and facilities belonging to them, the design of the colours are:\n\n* Queen's/King's Colour - Scarlet with the regimental insignia, arms and battle honours\n* Regimental Colors - Union Jack with regimental insignia and any battle honours\n\nUnlike most infantry regiments all five carry all battle honours on both colours.\n\nUntil the 1820s, the Guards infantry carried company colours alongside the regimental battalion colours.\n\nA 3rd colour, the Guards State Colour, is only used when the Queen and the Duke of Edinburgh are present. Only the Grenadier, Coldstream and Scots Guards use them. Their design is scarlet with the regimental insignia and arms at the centre with the Royal Cypher at the corners.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==See also==\n* [[Colours, standards and guidons]]\n\n[[Category:Military of the United Kingdom]]\n", "text_old": "[[File:Commonwealth Heads of Government Meeting MOD 45164080.jpg|thumb|The Queen's colour of the [[Coldstream Guards]].]]\nThe '''Regulation Colours''' are the standard colours used in the armed forces of the countries falling under the [[Commonwealth of Nations]].\n\n== [[British Armed Forces]] colours ==\n\n[[United Kingdom]] [[military]] units usually carry two '''Regulation Colours'''. These are the Regulation Queen's Colour and Regulation Regimental Colour. These are often referred to as the [[standard (flag)|standard]] or [[ensign]].\n\nColours are the identifying [[war flag|battle flag]]s carried by military [[regiment]]s to show where their respective [[troops]] should rally in battle. Originally these were 6'6\" x 6' in size, though have now been reduced to 3'9\" x 3', as regiments no longer carry their colours on the battlefield.\n\n=== British Army ===\n\nPrior to 1743, each infantry regiment of the [[British Army]] was responsible for the design and quantity of standards carried, often with each company having its own design. In that year King [[George II of Great Britain|George II]] issued a [[Warrant (law)|royal warrant]] to require each regiment to have, as their first colour, the King's colour. It was also to consist of the [[Union Jack]] throughout, as a symbol of royal allegiance. The second colour was to be the colour of the facings (uniform linings) of each Regiment, with the Union flag in the upper canton. When Regiments had red or white facings, this was to be replaced by the red cross of [[St George]] on a white background. Regiments with \"Royal\" designation or named after the members of the royal family, regardless of facings, used blue regimental colours (plus the optional Union Jack canton), Irish regiments green facings.\n\nA second royal warrant was issued in 1747, requiring the Regimental number to be displayed on the colours. As many regiments at that time were known by the name of the Regimental Colonel instead of a number, this requirement was often ignored. On 1 July 1751 a third royal warrant was issued stating ''\"No Colonel is to put his Arms, Crest, Device, or Livery on any part of the Appointments of the Regiment under his Command.\"'' Company colours were phased out altogether, with the battalion colours of the regiment using the designs issused being the only sanctioned ones used.\n\nOver time, these colours have evolved to include the battle honours s awarded to each Regiment, though these have also been limited.\n\n[[File:DWR Regimental Colours RLH.jpg|thumb|600px|Colours of the [[Duke of Wellington's Regiment]]]]\nOnly one British Regiment carries more than two colours on parade. This is the [[Yorkshire Regiment]], who carry four colours. The second pair consists of a stand of honorary battle flags, which are the original size of 6'6\" x 6'. These honorary colours, 'Queen's Honorary Colour' and 'Regimental Honorary Colour,' were originally awarded to the [[76th Regiment of Foot]], which later became the 2nd Battalion of the [[Duke of Wellington's Regiment|Duke of Wellington's (West Riding Regiment)]] in 1808, by the Honorable [[British East India Company|East India Company]] for their distinguished services during the [[Battle of Ally Ghur]] and again at [[Delhi]] between 1802 and 1804.<ref>[http://www.army.mod.uk/documents/general/YORKS_Honorary_Colours.pdf British Army website - Yorks Honorary Colours]</ref> In 1948 the 1st and 2nd Battalions merged and retained the Honorary Colours. In 2006 the Duke of Wellington's Regiment merged with the [[Prince of Wales's Own Regiment of Yorkshire]] and the [[Green Howards]] to form the 'Yorkshire Regiment (14th/15th, 19th and 33rd/76th Foot)'.<ref>[http://www.army.mod.uk/infantry/regiments/26215.aspx British Army website - Yorkshire Regiment History]</ref>\n\nLight infantry regiments (today [[The Rifles]]) plus the [[Brigade of Gurkhas]] do not use colours at all owing to their role (the latter, however, carries the Queen's Truncheon awarded in 1857 instead).\n\n==== [[Guards Division]] ====\nUnlike the rest of the Army, all five [[Foot Guards]] infantry regiments sport a different variant pattern.\n\nGiven the status of the guards regiments as units under royal patronage and for the defence of the British Royal Family and facilities belonging to them, the design of the colours are:\n\n* Queen's/King's Colour - Scarlet with the regimental insignia, arms and battle honours\n* Regimental Colors - Union Jack with regimental insignia and any battle honours\n\nUnlike most infantry regiments all five carry all battle honours on both colours.\n\nUntil the 1820s, the Guards infantry carried company colours alongside the regimental battalion colours.\n\nA 3rd colour, the Guards State Colour, is only used when the Queen and the Duke of Edinburgh are present. Only the Grenadier, Coldstream and Scots Guards use them. Their design is scarlet with the regimental insignia and arms at the centre with the Royal Cypher at the corners.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==See also==\n* [[Colours, standards and guidons]]\n\n[[Category:Military of the United Kingdom]]\n", "name_user": "Will Sandberg", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Regulation_Colours"}
{"title_page": "B\u02bcutz Aj Sak Chiik", "text_new": "{{Infobox royalty\n| name =B\u02bcutz Aj Sak Chiik\n| title =[[Ajaw]] of [[Palenque]]\n| image = Glifo de B'utz Aj Sak Chiik en tablero del Templo XVII.jpg\n| caption = Glyph of B\u02bcutz Aj Sak Chiik at Temple XVII Tablet (see vectorised version [[Commons:File:B'utz Aj Sak Chiik.svg|here)]]\n| reign =July 28, 487 \u2013 501\n| coronation =\n| full name = \n| predecessor =[[Casper (Maya ruler)|\"Casper\"]]\n| successor =[[Ahkal Mo\u02bc Nahb I]]\n| brother =Ahkal Mo\u02bc Nahb I?\n| birth_date =November 15, 459\n| birth_place =\n| death_date =501?\n| religion = [[Maya religion]]\n|}}\n'''B\u02bcutz Aj Sak Chiik''',<ref group=\"N\">The ruler's name, when transcribed is '''bu-tz\u02bca-ja-SAK-chi[ku]''', translated \"Smoking White/Resplendent Coati?\".</ref> also known as '''Manik''', (November 15, 459 \u2013 501?), was an ''[[ajaw]]'' of the [[Maya civilization|Maya]] city of [[Palenque]]. He took the throne on July 28, 487, reigning until 501. He was likely the brother of Ahkal Mo\u02bc Nahb I.<ref group=\"N\">These are the dates indicated on the Maya inscriptions in [[Mesoamerican Long Count calendar]], Born: 9.1.4.5.0 12 Ahaw 13 Sak and Acceded: 9.2.12.6.18 3 Etz\u02bcnab 11 Xul.</ref><ref name=Skidmore1>{{cite book|last1=Skidmore|first1=Joel|title=The Rulers of Palenque|date=2010|publisher=Mesoweb Publications|pages=18\u201319|edition=Fifth|url=http://www.mesoweb.com/palenque/resources/rulers/PalenqueRulers-05.pdf|accessdate=12 October 2015}}</ref>\n\n== Notes ==\n{{Reflist|group=\"N\"}}\n\n== Sources ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-reg}}\n{{succession box|title=[[Palenque#Dynastic list|Ajaw of Palenque]] | before=[[Casper (Maya ruler)|\"Casper\"]]|after=[[Ahkal Mo\u02bc Nahb I]]|years=July 28, 487 \u2013 501}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{Rulers of Palenque}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Butz Aj Sak Chiik}}\n[[Category:Rulers of Palenque]]\n[[Category:459 births]]\n[[Category:501 deaths]]\n[[Category:6th-